    "prompt": "<div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows, from right to left, the front view of a screen with an interference pattern on it and with an arrow pointing to the Central Bright Maximum, a screen, an obstruction with two slits, and then a monochromatic light. There are two dashed lines, labeled D sub 1 and D sub 2, drawn from the screen to the slits in the obstruction. A note states that the figure is not drawn to scale.\" src=\"/images/31b1a18d0ea9830739ff69c00e46d923.svg\"></div></div></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Monochromatic light is incident upon two narrow, closely-spaced slits, as shown in the figure. An interference pattern is generated on a screen some distance away from the slits, and is shown on the far right of the figure. The two slits are distances of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"D sub 1\"><math alttext=\"D sub 1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><msub><mi>D</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mstyle></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"D sub 2\"><math alttext=\"D sub 2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>D</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></span></span> from the center of the first-order bright fringe–that is, the bright fringe adjacent to the central bright maximum − in the interference pattern. The path length difference for the two paths indicated by the dashed lines is therefore <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"D sub 2, end sub, minus, D sub 1, end sub\"><math alttext=\"D sub 2, end sub, minus, D sub 1, end sub\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>D</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>−</mo><msub><mi>D</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math></span></span>.</p><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">The spacing between the two slits is then changed so that, using the same light source, a new interference pattern is created. In the new interference pattern, the spacing between adjacent bright fringes is twice as much as it was in the original pattern. In this second configuration, what is the path length difference for the paths from each slit to the new position of the first-order bright fringe?</p>\n",
